'''Kawachi Kunitama Shrine''' (かわちくにたまじんじゃ / かわちのくにたまじんじゃ, 河内國魂神社) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kunitama-dōri, {{ill|lt=Nada Ward|Q1154555|qid=Q1154555|1=Nada-ku, Kobe}}, {{ill|lt=Kobe|Q48320|qid=Q48320|1=Kobe}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|qid=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. It was formerly called “Gomō Tenjin” or “Gomō Tenjinsha.”

“Gomō” is said to derive from the old local place name “Gomau.”

=== Enshrined deities ===
The shrine enshrines {{ill|Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|qid=Q276944|1=Ōkuninushi}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona|qid=Q3275687}}, and {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}. It does not enshrine {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amahikone-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}, ancestral deity of the {{ill|lt=Oshikōchi clan|Q11395444|qid=Q11395444|1=Ōshikōchi clan}} ({{ill|lt=Oshikōchi no kuni no miyatsuko|Q11395443|qid=Q11395443|1=Funi-kawachi-no-Kuni-no-Miyatsuko}}), nor his child {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amemikage-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}.

=== History ===
In the Kyōhō era, in ''{{ill|lt=Gokinaishi|Q11372555|qid=Q11372555|lt=Nihon Yochi Tsūshi Kinai-hen|1=Five Kinai Chronicles}}'' (Gokinaishi), {{ill|lt=Namikawa Seisho|Q6563872|qid=Q6563872|1=Namikawa Seisho}} identified Gomō Tenjin with Kawachi Kunitama Shrine worshiped by the Oshikōchi clan. In September {{ill|lt=1736|Q6989|qid=Q6989|1=1736}} ({{ill|lt=Genbun|Q1145754|qid=Q1145754|1=Genbun}} 1), local village headmen were summoned to the Osaka magistrate and reportedly had the name imposed on them by force.

About 2.5 km east, in Mikage, {{ill|lt=Higashinada Ward|Q277434|qid=Q277434|1=Higashinada-ku, Kobe}}, behind {{ill|lt=Tsunashiki Tenman Shrine (Kobe)|Q17229186|qid=Q17229186|lt=Tsunashiki Tenman Shrine|1=Tsunashiki Tenman Shrine}}, there is a hilly area called Mikage-yama; there is also a theory that this may have been the true Kawachi Kunitama Shrine.

